## §30 Layers Panel — Drag-to-Reorder + Drop-into-Empty-Container

**Features implemented:**
- Every `LayerRow` has `draggable` and full HTML5 DnD handlers (`onDragStart`, `onDragOver`, `onDrop`, `onDragEnd`).
- `LayerDragState` tracks `{ dragId, dropTargetId, dropPosition: 'above' | 'inside' | 'below' }`.
- Container rows use **thirds**: top 33% = above (blue top border), middle 34% = inside (blue outline), bottom 33% = below (blue bottom border). Non-container rows use top/bottom halves only.
- `handleLayerDrop` handles all three positions:
  - `'above'` / `'below'` → insert at `targetIdx` / `targetIdx + 1` in target's parent
  - `'inside'` → `moveNode(dragId, dropTargetId, childCount)` — works even when the container has zero children
- Chevron icon size increased from 8px → 13px.

**Click-to-deselect:** The scrollable tree wrapper (`data-testid="layers-tree"`) has an `onClick` that calls `store.select(null)` when the click doesn't land on any `[data-layer-row]` element. Every `LayerRow` root `div` has `data-layer-row` to enable this check.

**Multi-select in layers:** When `dragId` is in the current `selectedIds` AND `selectedIds.length > 1`, `handleLayerDrop` calls `moveNodes(selectedIds, ...)` instead of `moveNode`.

**Rule:** `LAYER_CONTAINER_TYPES` (same set as `CONTAINER_TYPES` in `_canvas.tsx`) drives the thirds/halves decision. Keep it in sync when adding new container types.

---

## §31 moveNodeUp / moveNodeDown for Absolute Nodes

**Root cause:** Absolute nodes use DOM order as their stacking axis (later = higher z-index). So "Move Up" = bring forward = higher DOM index, and "Move Down" = send backward = lower DOM index. This is the OPPOSITE of flow nodes.

The old code had a shared early-return **before** checking `isAbsCls`:
- `moveNodeUp`:   `if (idx <= 0) return s` — blocked the FIRST abs node from bringing forward.
- `moveNodeDown`: `if (idx < 0 || idx >= siblings.length - 1) return s` — blocked the LAST abs node from sending backward.

**Fix:** Move `isAbsCls` check BEFORE the boundary guard, then use per-branch boundary conditions:
```typescript
const isAbsCls = (n: SDUINode) => /\b(absolute|fixed)\b/.test(...);
const currentIsAbs = isAbsCls(siblings[idx]);

// moveNodeDown:
if (currentIsAbs) {
  if (idx <= 0) return s;          // already at bottom of stacking order
  targetIdx = idx - 1;             // send backward = lower DOM index
} else {
  if (idx >= siblings.length - 1) return s;
  targetIdx = idx + 1;             // move later, skipping abs siblings
}

// moveNodeUp (inverted):
if (currentIsAbs) {
  if (idx >= siblings.length - 1) return s;  // already on top
  targetIdx = idx + 1;                        // bring forward = higher DOM index
} else {
  if (idx <= 0) return s;
  targetIdx = idx - 1;            // move earlier, skipping abs siblings
}
```

For flow nodes, the target index additionally skips over any `absolute`/`fixed` siblings in the chosen direction, so the user's reorder produces a visible layout change.

**Rule:** Always compute `currentIsAbs` before any early return in `moveNodeUp`/`moveNodeDown`. The correct boundary for an abs node in "Move Down" is `idx <= 0` (not `idx >= length-1`).

