## §35 Formula Binding — `FieldWithBinding`, `ToggleBind`, and Class-Based Fields

### FieldWithBinding — Two Layout Modes

`FieldWithBinding` in `_formula-panel.tsx` wraps any input with a bind icon (≈). When a formula is applied the input is replaced by "ƒ Edit formula".

- **Default layout** (no `stackLayout`): children + ≈ side-by-side. Use for number/text inputs where the bind icon can sit to the right.
- **Stack layout** (`stackLayout`): displayLabel + ≈ on top row, children or "ƒ Edit formula" below. Use when children are wide (toggle button groups, 9-cell grids, direction buttons) to prevent horizontal overflow.

**Rule:** Never put `FieldWithBinding` (which has `flex: 1`) inside a header row (`justifyContent: space-between`) alongside a `SectionHeader`. The FieldWithBinding expands and the "ƒ Edit formula" button inflates the header when bound. Instead:
1. Place `SectionHeader` alone at the top.
2. Place `FieldWithBinding` with `stackLayout` below it, with the interactive controls as its children.

```tsx
// ❌ BAD — FieldWithBinding in header row inflates it when bound
<div style={{ display: 'flex', justifyContent: 'space-between' }}>
  <SectionHeader title="Self Alignment" />
  <FieldWithBinding label="selfAlignment" ...><span /></FieldWithBinding>
</div>
{!isBound && <div>toggles</div>}

// ✅ GOOD — SectionHeader alone, FieldWithBinding wraps toggles with stackLayout
<SectionHeader title="Self Alignment" />
<FieldWithBinding label="selfAlignment" stackLayout ...>
  <div style={{ display: 'flex', gap: 4 }}>{toggles}</div>
</FieldWithBinding>
```

This applies to: **Self Alignment**, **Alignment** (9-cell grid), **Auto Layout** (direction buttons).

---

### ToggleBind — Compact Row for Toggle + Bind

For sections that are a simple on/off toggle (Visible, Disabled, Repeat/List, Clip content), use the `ToggleBind` component defined in `_panel-right.tsx`.

```tsx
<ToggleBind
  rowLabel="Visible"
  fieldId="visibility-condition"
  hint="e.g. {{isLoggedIn}}"
  expectedType="boolean"
  isOn={!isHidden}
  value={formulaValue}
  onToggle={() => /* toggle the boolean */}
  onChange={v => /* handle FormulaValue */}
/>
```

Renders: `LABEL | [toggle or ƒ Edit formula] [≈]` — all tightly grouped on the right (no flex-1 expansion).

**Rule:** Never use `FieldWithBinding` for toggle+bind rows. It has `flex: 1` which floats the ≈ icon to the far right. Use `ToggleBind` instead.

---

### Class-Based Field Binding (`classFormulas` sidecar)

Style-based fields (width, color, etc.) store `{ formula: "..." }` directly in `node.props.style.*`. Class-based fields (selfAlignment, textAlign, shadow, etc.) cannot store formulas in `className` (which is always a plain string).

**Solution:** `node.props.classFormulas` is a sidecar object that stores formula bindings for class-based fields:

```ts
node.props.classFormulas = {
  selfAlignment: { formula: '"self-center"' },
  textAlign: { formula: '"text-center"' },
}
```

**`bindOrPatchCls(fieldKey, applyFn, v)`** in `_panel-right.tsx` manages writes:
- If `v` is a formula → stores in `props.classFormulas[fieldKey]`, evaluates immediately, calls `applyFn(evaluated)`
- If `v` is a plain string → clears `props.classFormulas[fieldKey]`, calls `applyFn(v)`

**Renderer** (`lib/sdui/renderer.tsx`) reads `classFormulas` after `cleanProps` is assembled and merges evaluated classes into `className`:
```ts
for (const [, fv] of Object.entries(classFormulas)) {
  if (fv?.formula) extraCls += ' ' + evaluateFormula(fv.formula, state).value;
}
cleanProps.className = mergeTailwindClasses(className, extraCls.trim());
```

**Rule:** Every `FieldWithBinding` for a class-based property must:
1. Read `value` from `(classFormulas?.['fieldKey'] as FormulaValue) ?? derivedToken`
2. Call `bindOrPatchCls('fieldKey', applyFn, v)` in `onChange`

---

### Rules of Hooks — No Early Returns Before Hooks

**Problem:** React throws "change in order of Hooks" when a component has an early `return null` BEFORE a hook call (`useState`, `useCallback`, etc.).

**Fix:** Always call ALL hooks unconditionally before any early return.

```tsx
// ❌ BAD
function DisableInDesign({ node }) {
  const store = useBuilderStore();
  if (!INTERACTIVE_TYPES.has(node.type)) return null;  // early return
  const [state, setState] = useState(false);           // hook after return!
}

// ✅ GOOD
function DisableInDesign({ node }) {
  const store = useBuilderStore();
  const [state, setState] = useState(false);           // all hooks first
  if (!INTERACTIVE_TYPES.has(node.type)) return null;  // early return after
}
```

---

## §36 Visibility — Force Show in Editor

When a node has a `condition` (formula or `false`), the Visible section shows a sub-toggle: **"Force show in editor"**.

- Toggle ON → sets `node._forceShowInEditor = true`
- Toggle OFF → removes the field

In `lib/sdui/renderer.tsx`, before condition evaluation:
```ts
const forceShow = builderMode && node._forceShowInEditor === true;
if (!forceShow) {
  if ((node.condition as unknown) === false) return null;
  if (node.condition != null && !evaluateCondition(node.condition, sduiContext)) return null;
}
```

**Rule:** `_forceShowInEditor` is a builder-only field. The exported JSON still has the real `condition`, so production behaviour is unaffected. Use amber toggle colour (`#f59e0b`) to visually distinguish it from normal blue toggles.

---

## §37 Repeat / List — Plain String Map Paths

Existing JSONs store `map` as a plain string (e.g. `"map": "store.products"`). `RepeatInDesign` normalises it for display:

```ts
const mapFormulaValue: FormulaValue = isBoundValue(mapValue)
  ? mapValue                              // already a formula object
  : typeof mapValue === 'string' && mapValue
    ? { formula: mapValue }              // wrap plain string for editor display
    : false;                             // no map → toggle OFF
```

When saving, simple dot-paths are stored back as plain strings (not formula objects):
```ts
const isSimplePath = /^[\w$.]+$/.test(formulaString.trim());
store.patchNodeField(nodeId, 'map', isSimplePath ? formulaString : { formula: formulaString });
```

**Rule:** Never require users to update existing JSON. Normalise plain-string `map` values to `{ formula }` for editor display and unwrap back to plain strings when saving simple paths.

