## §44 Form System — Button Submit Type

### Builder configuration

Button nodes in the Settings tab show a "Submit" on/off toggle. When ON:
- `node.props.submitType = 'submit'` is set
- Clicking the button in preview calls the parent `FormContainer`'s `submitForm` action

### Default on drop

When a `FormContainer` is dropped onto the canvas, its default children include a `Button` with `submitType: 'submit'` already set. This avoids the user needing to manually configure the submit button.

### Runtime behaviour in `renderer.tsx`

```tsx
if (resolvedProps.submitType === 'submit' && formCtx) {
  // Wrap onClick to call formCtx.submit() before any configured action
  const originalClick = resolvedProps.onClick;
  resolvedProps.onClick = () => {
    formCtx.submit();
    originalClick?.();
  };
}
```

**Rule:** `submitType` is a builder convention. The SDUI JSON schema does not have a native `submitType` prop — the renderer intercepts it before passing props to the component.

---

## §45 Form System — Disabled Overlay

### How it works

When `props.disabled` is truthy (or `_forceDisabledInEditor` is set in builder mode), the renderer wraps the element in a `position: relative` container and places a configurable overlay `div` on top.

### CSS rules

**Critical:** Use `rgba()` background, NOT separate `backgroundColor` + `opacity` CSS properties.

With a separate `opacity` property, the browser composites the entire element (including `backdrop-filter`) at that opacity level, which makes the blur effect invisible at low opacity values.

```tsx
// ❌ BAD — opacity composites the blur too
{ backgroundColor: '#000000', opacity: 0.3, backdropFilter: 'blur(8px)' }

// ✅ GOOD — rgba keeps blur at full strength independently
{ backgroundColor: `rgba(${r}, ${g}, ${b}, ${alpha})`, backdropFilter: 'blur(8px)' }
```

Always add both `backdropFilter` and `WebkitBackdropFilter` for Safari support.

### `pointerEvents` by mode

```tsx
pointerEvents: builderMode ? 'none' : 'all',
```

In builder mode the transparent capture overlay handles all click-to-select events. Setting `'none'` lets those events pass through the disabled overlay to the capture overlay beneath it, so the user can still select the disabled element in the canvas.

In preview/production mode `'all'` ensures the overlay truly blocks interaction with the disabled element.

### `_forceDisabledInEditor`

When `props.disabled` is formula-bound (not literally `true`), the overlay doesn't show in the builder because the formula evaluates to a non-boolean at design time. The "Force show in editor" checkbox sets `node._forceDisabledInEditor = true`, which makes the renderer show the overlay unconditionally in builder mode.

```tsx
const showDisabledOverlay =
  resolvedProps.disabled === true ||
  (node._forceDisabledInEditor === true && builderMode);
```

**Rule:** Only show the "Force show in editor" checkbox when `isBound` is true (the disabled prop is a formula). When disabled is a plain boolean, the overlay automatically reflects the value.

### Overlay configuration — Performance rules

All three overlay properties (color, opacity, blur) use **rAF-throttled live updates** + **single history commit on gesture end**:

```
patchColorLive  → rAF → patchNodeFieldLive  ──────────────── onCommit (picker closes) → _pushHistory
patchOpacityLive→ rAF → patchNodeFieldLive  ── onMouseUp / onBlur → _pushHistory
patchBlurLive   → rAF → patchNodeFieldLive  ── onMouseUp / onBlur → _pushHistory
```

- **`patchNodeFieldLive`** — updates the node tree in Zustand but does NOT call `_pushHistory`. Use for all continuous drag/slide updates.
- **`_pushHistory`** — call exactly once per gesture (on mouseup, blur, or color picker close) so undo/redo gets one clean snapshot per change.

**Rule:** Never call `patchNodeField` (which calls `_pushHistory`) during a drag gesture. Flooding history with per-pixel snapshots makes undo useless and causes jank from repeated deep-clones of the node tree.

### Color picker for overlay

Use `FigmaColorPicker` (not native `<input type="color">`) so the user has access to theme swatches. Pass `onCommit` to push history when the picker popover closes:

```tsx
<FigmaColorPicker
  value={overlay.color ?? '#000000'}
  onChange={hex => patchColorLive(hex)}
  onCommit={commitHistory}
/>
```

`onCommit` is implemented in `FigmaColorPicker` via a ref-stable callback that fires when `open` transitions from `true` → `false` (regardless of whether the popover was closed by clicking outside or pressing Escape).

---

## §46 Form System — `patchNodeFieldLive` vs `patchNodeField`

Two store methods exist for patching a node field:

| Method | History | Use for |
|---|---|---|
| `patchNodeField(id, field, value)` | Yes — calls `_pushHistory` | Discrete changes (checkbox toggle, dropdown select, text commit on blur) |
| `patchNodeFieldLive(id, field, value)` | No | Continuous drag/slide updates (slider drag, color picker circle) |

**Rule:** When building any panel control that involves continuous user gestures (range slider, drag handle, color picker), always use `patchNodeFieldLive` for the onChange handler and call `store._pushHistory()` once in `onMouseUp` / `onBlur` / `onCommit`.

This prevents:
1. **History flooding** — undo jumps only milliseconds back instead of to the state before the gesture
2. **Performance jank** — `_pushHistory` does a full deep-clone of the page node tree; calling it 60x/sec causes visible lag

